13
00:02:23,632 --> 00:02:30,114
[SPEAKER_04]: Africa needs to close the income gaps with the high-income world

14
00:02:30,998 --> 00:02:34,999
[SPEAKER_04]: And it needs to do that in a short period of time.

15
00:02:35,019 --> 00:02:44,562
[SPEAKER_04]: By that I mean a quarter century or the next 40 years to very significantly close the income gaps.

16
00:02:45,162 --> 00:02:58,986
[SPEAKER_04]: But for that to be accomplished, Africa needs a very strong pro-investment strategy in which the investments are comprehensive in human capital,

17
00:02:59,738 --> 00:03:06,760
[SPEAKER_04]: in physical infrastructure and of course in all of the main business sectors as well.

18
00:03:07,580 --> 00:03:28,846
[SPEAKER_04]: But my view is that the business investment both domestically generated and foreign direct investment will come on the basis of a strong physical infrastructure and on the basis of rising skills in

19
00:03:29,226 --> 00:03:31,808
[SPEAKER_04]: the young African workforce.

20
00:03:32,389 --> 00:03:56,590
[SPEAKER_04]: And that means a major focus on education both in universalizing secondary school completion, extending university level education to 30 to 40% of the high school finishers, and spurring very consciously

21
00:03:57,394 --> 00:04:07,900
[SPEAKER_04]: an innovation agenda through new science and technology funding and through an industrial policy that is satisfactory.

22
00:04:08,740 --> 00:04:11,762
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, how can all of this be accomplished?

23
00:04:11,782 --> 00:04:17,405
[SPEAKER_04]: Because it sounds like a wish list, not necessarily a policy agenda.

24
00:04:18,245 --> 00:04:25,009
[SPEAKER_04]: And my view is that everything depends on the success of Africa-wide integration.

25
00:04:26,910 --> 00:04:39,561
[SPEAKER_04]: could be possible for a few countries in Africa to succeed without Africa-wide success, but not for very many.

26
00:04:40,562 --> 00:04:53,294
[SPEAKER_04]: Much of Africa absolutely will not be able to move forward except in an Africa-wide macroeconomic boom, and that is

27
00:04:53,862 --> 00:05:23,122
[SPEAKER_04]: also for physical reasons, so much of Africa is inland, so many countries are landlocked, so many depend on an Africa-wide physical infrastructure, but also the more basic economic fact that across all economic sectors, from mining to manufacturing to finance and services to the new AI-based economy, scale matters.

28
00:05:23,922 --> 00:05:43,953
[SPEAKER_04]: And Africa as 54 individual member states of the AU will not make it, but Africa as a unified strategy of 1.5 billion people today and 2.5 billion people at mid-century will make it.

29
00:05:44,573 --> 00:05:46,994
[SPEAKER_04]: And that will be a very substantial market.

30
00:05:47,555 --> 00:05:53,598
[SPEAKER_04]: And I believe in the second half of this century, Africa will be one of the great poles of economic growth

31
00:05:54,310 --> 00:06:15,539
[SPEAKER_04]: and will be a centerpiece of the world economy, because Africa will rise to more than 30% of the world population, and I want to see Africa rise to an equivalent proportion of the world economy, which can happen towards the end of this century, but based on an investment-led strategy.

32
00:06:16,499 --> 00:06:23,482
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, right now, this is not the way that the world operates, and it's not the way that Africa operates, primarily.

33
00:06:24,002 --> 00:06:28,685
[SPEAKER_04]: because most of African decision-making is still at the national level.

34
00:06:29,405 --> 00:06:35,568
[SPEAKER_04]: I would say the AU level is aspirational but not as operational as it needs to be.

35
00:06:36,869 --> 00:06:48,355
[SPEAKER_04]: Cross-border investments, say on large projects like Grand Inga and many others, don't really work effectively.

36
00:06:48,495 --> 00:06:53,578
[SPEAKER_04]: Countries invest one by one, usually with limited means,

37
00:06:54,206 --> 00:07:19,053
[SPEAKER_04]: with the very narrow domestic financial markets and with a lot of advice coming from Washington saying, don't borrow, don't be too ambitious, don't get ahead of yourselves, you don't really need electricity, you don't really need all these investments, you need stability, which is an argument I disagree with entirely.

38
00:07:19,793 --> 00:07:22,874
[SPEAKER_04]: Africa needs rapid economic development.

39
00:07:23,722 --> 00:07:28,045
[SPEAKER_04]: doesn't need stability and poverty, doesn't need slow growth.

40
00:07:28,385 --> 00:07:36,771
[SPEAKER_04]: It needs a high growth agenda backed by an adequate financing structure.

41
00:07:37,832 --> 00:07:44,357
[SPEAKER_04]: So Kevin, of course, and colleagues, that raises many practical questions.

42
00:07:44,877 --> 00:07:50,021
[SPEAKER_04]: But finance stands at the center of those questions.

43
00:07:50,701 --> 00:07:51,742
[SPEAKER_04]: It's easy to say,

44
00:07:52,778 --> 00:07:58,740
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, Professor Sachs, we need more investment, but we can't even borrow what we have right now.

45
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:00,901
[SPEAKER_04]: We're in debt crisis and so forth.

46
00:08:01,922 --> 00:08:05,423
[SPEAKER_04]: I think all of that actually needs to be rethought.

47
00:08:06,043 --> 00:08:22,150
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't have time to elaborate all of my ideas, but my basic thought is that if we understood Africa to be a high growth economy, then everything that looks risky today

48
00:08:22,814 --> 00:08:28,218
[SPEAKER_04]: would not look so risky in the context of a rapid growth trajectory.

49
00:08:29,038 --> 00:08:35,683
[SPEAKER_04]: If Africa's growing at 7% per year, it's doubling every 10 years.

50
00:08:35,763 --> 00:08:39,565
[SPEAKER_04]: If it's growing at 10% per year, it's doubling every seven years.

51
00:08:40,306 --> 00:08:52,034
[SPEAKER_04]: And what looks like a high debt-to-GDP ratio today, in 50 years, we'll see very, very small, because the denominator

52
00:08:52,738 --> 00:08:57,741
[SPEAKER_04]: the GDP will have grown so markedly over that period.

53
00:08:58,502 --> 00:09:00,603
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the IMF gets this wrong.

54
00:09:01,244 --> 00:09:05,607
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think that the credit rating agencies also get this wrong.

55
00:09:06,547 --> 00:09:13,972
[SPEAKER_04]: And because of that, Africa is advised don't borrow or can't access adequate capital.

56
00:09:14,533 --> 00:09:22,438
[SPEAKER_04]: And this becomes a kind of self-fulfilling prophecy of high cost of capital, low borrowing, low growth,

57
00:09:22,962 --> 00:09:25,364
[SPEAKER_04]: and therefore perception of high risks.

58
00:09:26,065 --> 00:09:39,557
[SPEAKER_04]: And I believe we need to turn this around to understand the high growth potential, therefore the much lower risks, therefore the access to low-cost, long-term financing.

59
00:09:39,837 --> 00:09:44,862
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, there are many, many things to say about how to make such financing.

60
00:09:45,466 --> 00:09:53,748
[SPEAKER_04]: Some of it is really domestic resource mobilization in budgets over a period of 10 or 20 or 30 years.

61
00:09:53,968 --> 00:10:13,514
[SPEAKER_04]: For example, I believe that the way to finance education today is to say that those young children who will get a public finance education will pay a payroll tax 20 years from now when they're in the labor market and a modest payroll tax of 10% of their earnings

62
00:10:14,430 --> 00:10:16,631
[SPEAKER_04]: would pay for their education today.

63
00:10:17,291 --> 00:10:25,433
[SPEAKER_04]: So essentially you would finance universal education, not out of the current budget, but out of future payroll taxes.

64
00:10:25,833 --> 00:10:27,474
[SPEAKER_04]: That's just one example.

65
00:10:28,234 --> 00:10:42,238
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think that there are many ways to mobilize more financing within Africa's own capital markets, but not one country at a time, but through regional integration of the capital market,

66
00:10:43,322 --> 00:11:01,913
[SPEAKER_04]: as well as to have long-term, external finance based on rapid growth scenarios and a specific plan of action on building out the infrastructure and building out the human capital of Africa.

67
00:11:02,453 --> 00:11:11,418
[SPEAKER_04]: So I believe that we can design a high growth trajectory with what looks like quite high borrowing

68
00:11:12,118 --> 00:11:41,022
[SPEAKER_04]: both domestically and abroad for financing that high investment rate, which I'd like to see at around 40% of GDP, but that all of that makes sense when you realize that the resulting economic growth is going to be prolonged and rapid, because then what looks like excessive debt burdens

69
00:11:41,686 --> 00:11:46,308
[SPEAKER_04]: become actually quite modest when looked at the long-term perspective.

70
00:11:47,548 --> 00:11:59,513
[SPEAKER_04]: One reason why the IMF gets this wrong is that its own debt sustainability framework takes a short-term horizon, usually five to 10 years.

71
00:12:00,234 --> 00:12:05,095
[SPEAKER_04]: It asks, what will the debt-GDP ratio be in five years or what will it be in 10 years?

72
00:12:05,516 --> 00:12:06,836
[SPEAKER_04]: But that's the wrong question.

73
00:12:07,616 --> 00:12:11,198
[SPEAKER_04]: The question should be, what will it be in 30 years or 50 years?

74
00:12:12,178 --> 00:12:16,702
[SPEAKER_04]: and how to find the long-term financing to accomplish that.

75
00:12:17,903 --> 00:12:26,029
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, in terms of the continental scale resource mobilization, let me just make a few quick points.

76
00:12:26,610 --> 00:12:41,522
[SPEAKER_04]: First, I do believe that there can be tax reform throughout the continent that raises the revenues of government and the share of GDP over time and that this would be advisable.

77
00:12:42,290 --> 00:13:08,422
[SPEAKER_04]: Second, I believe that if the mining contracts are done properly and done in a consistent continental scale, Africa could reap many percentage points of GDP in actually collecting royalties and income taxation from international capital at much more effective collection rates.

78
00:13:08,966 --> 00:13:37,530
[SPEAKER_04]: Of course, this is a matter of corruption, it's a matter of leakage, it's a matter of poorly designed mining contracts, but Africa essentially gives away so many of its crucial mineral resources right now because that's been the game of Europe and the United States, and there are too many companies operating in Africa with the Cayman Island post office box address

79
00:13:38,310 --> 00:13:46,073
[SPEAKER_04]: or some other tax haven post office box address, none of those should exist because Africa needs these revenues.

80
00:13:46,113 --> 00:13:48,754
[SPEAKER_04]: These are Africa's own mineral resources.

81
00:13:49,955 --> 00:13:58,098
[SPEAKER_04]: I do believe that the lending could be made much safer with financial and monetary integration in Africa.

82
00:13:58,638 --> 00:14:05,881
[SPEAKER_04]: Africa should aim for a unified currency, maybe over a period of 10 to 15 years.

83
00:14:06,381 --> 00:14:07,242
[SPEAKER_04]: It's time for this.

84
00:14:08,362 --> 00:14:11,023
[SPEAKER_04]: is working, it is the right model.

85
00:14:11,623 --> 00:14:13,984
[SPEAKER_04]: Africa should have an African currency.

86
00:14:14,525 --> 00:14:22,868
[SPEAKER_04]: Africa should not have its reserves held in France or any other foreign country.

87
00:14:23,408 --> 00:14:28,910
[SPEAKER_04]: Africa needs its monetary independence, but it also needs its monetary integration.

88
00:14:29,771 --> 00:14:37,494
[SPEAKER_04]: And so many crises in Africa have come because of liquidity crises, and these liquidity crises would be

89
00:14:38,170 --> 00:14:52,314
[SPEAKER_04]: avoided entirely with monetary integration and with effectively a functioning African central bank that could address what otherwise turned into uncontrolled tax.

90
00:14:53,554 --> 00:14:59,196
[SPEAKER_04]: And this, I think, is why monetary integration should be part of this strategy.

91
00:14:59,996 --> 00:15:07,358
[SPEAKER_04]: The last point I'd like to mention quickly, Kevin, is that in a multipolar world, Africa has many partners.

92
00:15:08,070 --> 00:15:14,492
And it shouldn't be told which partners those are by any of these individual places.

93
00:15:15,292 --> 00:15:26,055
[SPEAKER_04]: Neither the United States nor Europe should put sanctions on dealing with Russia or Iran or China or any other place.

94
00:15:26,875 --> 00:15:36,678
[SPEAKER_04]: This system of unilateral sanctions that the United States and the EU and UK have imposed is illegal and unacceptable.

95
00:15:37,442 --> 00:15:45,086
[SPEAKER_04]: The only sanctions that are truly sanctionable at the international level are those that are approved by the UN Security Council.

96
00:15:45,766 --> 00:15:59,214
[SPEAKER_04]: No country, not the United States or anybody else, should say to an African country, you can't trade with China, you can't trade with Iran, you can't trade with Russia or with anybody else.

97
00:15:59,834 --> 00:16:07,218
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think this is very hard one country at a time in Africa, but the African Union has a policy

98
00:16:07,970 --> 00:16:22,402
[SPEAKER_04]: should reject unilateral sanctions for any of the member states and use its diplomacy at the continental scale to reject such policies.

99
00:16:23,223 --> 00:16:37,034
[SPEAKER_04]: And then finally, Africa needs open trade and finance, as I say, from all of these partners, not only from traditional partners, but from new partners.

100
00:16:37,962 --> 00:16:44,465
[SPEAKER_04]: China is the lead trade partner for much of Africa already.

101
00:16:44,905 --> 00:16:54,109
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't have the count of how many countries that's true, but I would suspect that it is a substantial part of the continent already.

102
00:16:54,589 --> 00:16:56,330
[SPEAKER_04]: That's a big change of direction.

103
00:16:56,810 --> 00:17:02,712
[SPEAKER_04]: More generally, the rise of Asia means that India will play a larger role in Africa's trade.

104
00:17:03,073 --> 00:17:06,314
[SPEAKER_04]: China will play a larger role in Africa's trade.

105
00:17:06,646 --> 00:17:12,309
