149
00:22:31,806 --> 00:22:53,238
[SPEAKER_02]: So if we go out here and resolve as advisors to heads of states and governments, advisors to prime ministers, advisors and central deputies, central bank governors and chief economists to ensure that we encourage our heads of state and decision makers to operationalize this instrument.

150
00:22:54,378 --> 00:23:00,942
[SPEAKER_02]: That will take us a step to the dream that Jeff has for Africa and I hope we all share that dream.

151
00:23:01,834 --> 00:23:18,383
[SPEAKER_02]: He talked about the debt, and I also talked about the Africa financing stability mechanism that will help us to reduce the liquidity challenges that many countries face that often push them over the edge with regard to debt refinancing.

152
00:23:19,744 --> 00:23:22,045
[SPEAKER_02]: He also talked about the freedom of choice.

153
00:23:22,065 --> 00:23:30,430
[SPEAKER_02]: The discussion on whether China is good for Africa or US is good for Africa is irrelevant.

154
00:23:31,082 --> 00:23:37,807
[SPEAKER_02]: What is relevant is what does Africa want and who provides what Africa wants at that moment.

155
00:23:38,407 --> 00:23:42,711
[SPEAKER_02]: So it depends on the continent to have the freedom of choice.

156
00:23:43,231 --> 00:23:51,557
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think it's Amartya Sen who also defines this as the fact that one is not poor when you have the freedom to choose.

157
00:23:52,238 --> 00:23:57,862
[SPEAKER_02]: So the continent should have freedom of choice of trade partners and so on and so forth.

158
00:23:58,482 --> 00:24:01,323
[SPEAKER_02]: And to do that, he referred to economic diplomacy.

159
00:24:02,423 --> 00:24:15,207
[SPEAKER_02]: Economic diplomacy, to be able to pull our efforts together as a united continent, instead of negotiating as individual small countries in terms of economic power.

160
00:24:15,727 --> 00:24:27,670
[SPEAKER_02]: With regard to the multi-polarity factors we discussed in the morning, we'll pull together and have a united Africa-wide economic diplomacy we can use to push

161
00:24:28,262 --> 00:24:30,024
[SPEAKER_02]: our discussion.

162
00:24:30,724 --> 00:24:34,928
[SPEAKER_02]: Open trade with all partners without exception.

163
00:24:35,849 --> 00:24:53,664
[SPEAKER_02]: We have to look east, west, north, and south, not to copy, but to learn from the successes and mistakes that have been made so we can have the benefit of being the latecomer in the old development paradigm.

164
00:24:54,124 --> 00:24:56,146
[SPEAKER_02]: But the good thing about the multipolarity

165
00:24:56,606 --> 00:24:57,727
[SPEAKER_02]: that is happening now.

166
00:24:57,867 --> 00:24:58,848
[SPEAKER_02]: We are all together.

167
00:24:59,368 --> 00:25:01,130
